Bombarder in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Eloquence has always been one of the main strengths of American President Barack Obama.
However, it seems today that his words have led him into a trap.
After saying in March last year that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioning last year a "red line" that should not be crossed, Obama will lose face if he does not react energetically to the murder, attributed to the Syrian regime, of more than 1000 civilians with sarin gas.
Of course, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama get himself into such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
American Secretary of State John Kerry is right to qualify the use of gas as 'moral obscenity'.
But torturing children, precursors of civil war two years ago, is just as much so.
And is it morally more obscene to kill civilians with chemical products than to bomb them, shoot at them, or let them die of hunger?
It is commonly admitted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that certain weapons are more immoral than others.
Military weapons of mass destruction, nuclear bombs in particular, certainly cause more damage and more quickly than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing around 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more in a single night in Tokyo with incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas the Jews than to shoot them in mass graves?
A point of view, defended notably by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, is that a swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to give up using chemical weapons and return to "more ordinary means for massacring his people".
I don't think that makes any sense.
The question is surely that of massacre, not the methods used.
In any case, moral indignation, as justified as it may be, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the deaths of over 40 million Chinese in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sane person has suggested that a military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with the support of the United States.
Is it therefore a legal question? The use of chemical weapons is in fact a violation of international conventions, including the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, which Syria has never signed and the Geneva Protocol, to which it is a party.
There are therefore valid reasons to consider Assad as a war criminal, in which case he must be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), established, incidentally, by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But circumventing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not easily defendable policy.
One might however argue that the "international community", or Western countries, or the United States as the main Western power, must surely draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn a blind eye when innocent people are being mass murdered?
Tolerating genocide is not acceptable.
But where exactly do we draw the line?
How many murders constitute genocide?
Thousands?
Des centaines de milliers ?
Des millions ?
Ou bien le nombre n’entre-t-il pas en ligne de compte ?
Un génocide est après tout une question d’intention, il y a une volonté de tuer ou de persécuter des individus en raison de leur race, appartenance ethnique ou croyance.
En principe, tuer dix personnes pour ces motifs – ou même deux – constituerait une forme de génocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to think about before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance to improve the situation, save lives, and make the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether by sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
Responding to this implies asking: what is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
The intervention of the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" has a greater chance of producing a result in a weak country (such as Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a major power.
No one would consider launching missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of human rights or to enforce international norms and conventions on war.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
It is not a major power either.
But the civil war raging there has already spilled over its borders, involving more important countries, including Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
It is beyond doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is absolutely not certain that an American intervention would reduce the risk of a wider conflict.
In fact, some proponents of an American intervention – both neoconservatives and ‘liberal hawks’ – seem to desire the opposite: they call for a war with Iran.
And Obama has probably established a link in his mind between the red line on Syria and the one he drew for Iran, perhaps just as thoughtlessly, to prevent it from developing nuclear weapons.
What should we expect from US strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already indicated that they are not intended to bring down the Syrian regime?
They will not bring an end to the civil war.
But a single missile will be enough to make the United States a direct participant in this war, provoking a resurgence of violence.
Taking this risk to save Obama's honor does not seem particularly wise.
This point of view is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
This is the opinion of most Europeans.
And from a majority of Americans.
It's perhaps even Obama's opinion, which is why he is desperately trying to gain time, by delegating to the US Congress the authorization to use military force in Syria.
Since he took office, his relations with the Congress have been far from easy.
But he has more than ever today to cover his back.
